main_tweet:
How does COVID-19 spread? 

People can catch COVID-19 from others who have the virus. 

The disease can spread from person to person through small droplets from the nose or mouth which are spread when a person with COVID-19 coughs or exhales.

main_tweet:
WHAT IS COVID-19?
The 2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19), is an infectious disease caused by the severe acute respiratory syndrome.

WHAT ARE THE SYMPTOMS OF COVID-19? 
Cough or Sneeze
Shortness of breath or difficulty in breathing 
Fever 
Muscle pain

Droplets produced when an infected person coughs or sneezes 
There are two routes by which people could become infected:
Secretions can be directly transferred into the mouths or noses of people who are nearby (within 2 metres)", "created_at": 1584545769.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1240300973450551301, "tweet": "or could be inhaled into the lungs

main_tweet:
Remember: 

Seasonal flu is *very different* to pandemic flu.

If someone says "Covid-19 is just like the flu", check which one they're talking about.

If they mean "seasonal flu", take what they say with a bucketload of salt.
replies:
[{"tweet_id": 1233883513809584128, "tweet": "1918 Spanish flu: One of the worst pandemics in history, killed up to 50 million people

1957 Asian flu: Killed at least a million

1968 Hong Kong flu: Killed at least a million

1977 Russian flu: Less than a million deaths

2009 swine flu: Killed several hundred thousand", "created_at": 1583015728.0, "like_count": 8, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 2, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1233884365181968384, "tweet": "One of those five pandemics, the Russian flu, appears to have been just an old defrosted flu strain from a laboratory. People alive in the 1950s were immune, and the virus was weirdly similar to earlier ones. So really we're down to four truly novel pandemics.", "created_at": 1583015931.0, "like_count": 4, "reply_count": 2, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1233885679538466816, "tweet": "Anyone reading this has almost certainly lived through a pandemic, the H1N1 swine flu in 2009, but we were lucky there that it was extremely mild with a fatality rate not much different to seasonal flu.", "created_at": 1583016245.0, "like_count": 5, "reply_count": 3, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1233886228275027969, "tweet": "Fatality rates often fall as an epidemic spreads but it would be unwise to assume that case fatality in every pandemic will fall to swine flu levels. All the evidence so far suggests Covid-19 mortality is higher, by at least an order of magnitude.
 https://t.co/Pthp3Dwafs", "created_at": 1583016375.0, "like_count": 8, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 1, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1233886870599110656, "tweet": "So don't panic but please don't be complacent.

Virologists and epidemiologists are taking it far more seriously.

Coronaviruses are a large family of viruses that are known to cause illness ranging from the common cold to more severe diseases such as Middle East Respiratory Syndrome (MERS) and Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome (SARS).

The main way the disease spreads is through respiratory droplets expelled by someone who is coughing. The risk of catching COVID-19 from someone with no symptoms at all is very low.

What are the symptoms of COVID-19?
The most common symptoms of COVID-19 are fever, tiredness, and dry cough. Some patients may have aches and pains, nasal congestion, runny nose, sore throat or diarrhea. These symptoms are usually mild and begin gradually.

Human populations are NOT WELL-MIXED & HOMOGENOUS, so calcs give likely upper bound. 
Q: So what is herd immunity threshold (HIT) for real pops?
A: *Usually* lower & it depends on variation among individuals in 3 things: 1) contact rates; 2) susceptibility; 3) infectiousness.
